<paper id="1524408959"><title>Blobworld: A System for Region-Based Image Indexing and Retrieval</title><year>1999</year><authors><author org="University of California" id="2161208487">Chad Carson</author><author org="University of California" id="2522188702">Megan Thomas</author><author org="University of California" id="305618809">Serge Belongie</author><author org="University of California" id="2063640528">Joseph M. Hellerstein</author><author org="University of California" id="2136556746">Jitendra Malik</author></authors><n_citation>716</n_citation><doc_type>Journal</doc_type><references><reference>125925666</reference><reference>1533169541</reference><reference>1723433588</reference><reference>1947400014</reference><reference>2008297189</reference><reference>2068272887</reference><reference>2102475035</reference><reference>2118783153</reference><reference>2124101593</reference><reference>2126051390</reference><reference>2144679084</reference><reference>2151135734</reference><reference>2155776210</reference><reference>2238624099</reference><reference>2294259878</reference></references><venue id="106296714" type="J">Lecture Notes in Computer Science</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-48762-X_63</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.46156">Computer vision</keyword><keyword weight="0.63794">Automatic image annotation</keyword><keyword weight="0.56681">Color histogram</keyword><keyword weight="0.63772">Feature detection (computer vision)</keyword><keyword weight="0.46677">Pattern recognition</keyword><keyword weight="0.65689">Image texture</keyword><keyword weight="0.41963">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.57586">Image processing</keyword><keyword weight="0.54281">Search engine indexing</keyword><keyword weight="0.62207">Image retrieval</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Artificial intelligence</keyword><keyword weight="0.65626">Visual Word</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Blobworld is a system for image retrieval based on finding coherent image regions which roughly correspond to objects. Each image is automatically segmented into regions ("blobs") with associated color and texture descriptors. Queryingi s based on the attributes of one or two regions of interest, rather than a description of the entire image. In order to make large-scale retrieval feasible, we index the blob descriptions usinga tree. Because indexing in the high-dimensional feature space is computationally prohibitive, we use a lower-rank approximation to the high-dimensional distance. Experiments show encouraging results for both queryinga nd indexing.</abstract></paper>